post_text: The Board has voted that all students will begin the school year virtually on August 11th, with the potential to phase in in-person instruction following Labor Day if conditions allow.
text: The Board has voted that all students will begin the school year virtually on August 11th, with the potential to phase in in-person instruction following Labor Day if conditions allow.

post_text:
2020-21 Back to School Plan

At their meeting on Thursday, the School Board approved the Back to School schedule. The school schedule will begin a week later than originally planned in order to give families more time to review their options, allow schools additional time to plan, and also monitor the data trends of COVID-19.

School will begin for students on August 11, 2020 following our traditional in-person learning schedule. In addition, we will offer a virtual school option for parents/guardians who wish to make that selection. Students enrolled in the virtual program will follow the same calendar beginning on the same day, August 11th. Due to our delayed start, adjustments will be made to our previously scheduled Fall and Thanksgiving Break schedules.

If at any time it becomes necessary to pause in-person learning, we will be prepared to move to remote learning.

Please feel free to send any questions you may have to pthotline@pike.k12.in.us.

https://www.pike.k12.in.us/userfiles/-16/My%20Files/back%20to%20school.pdf?id=9530

United Against Racism

Marion County Public Schools have united to stand in solidarity with our communities to build a more just and compassionate world, to abolish racism, value social justice, and respect human dignity. The MSD of Pike Township is committed to equity, as stated in the Human Dignity Policy and through the work of the Equity Council. These are not isolated efforts, as we know this is ongoing work to create the change needed, and we look forward to working together.

Jasmyn Quarles will be continue her academic and athletic career as a soccer player at Anderson University. She plans to study Kinesiology/Pre-Chiropractic in preparation to become a Doctor of Naturopathic Medicine with a concentration in Chiropractic care.

During High School, Jasmyn was a 4 year starter on the Varsity women’s soccer team, serving as Captain of the team for 3 years. In addition, she was a two year member of the National Honors Society, and Girl’s Soccer representative on the Pike Athletic Council.

Jasmyn's awards include: 4 year letter winner, Fran A. Baur Sportsmanship Award, Girl’s Soccer Mental Attitude, Mic All-Conference Player, ISCA Academic All-State, All-Marion County Honorable mention

Jasmyn, we are so proud of and excited for you. Thank you for allowing us to be part of your journey.

#PikeProud #PikeFamily #ClassOf2020

Donovan Taylor will be attending Lincoln Technical Institute and taking the Collision Repair and Refinishing Technology course. His plan is to open his own repair shop and contract with insurance companies.

Donovan has been in Pike Township since first grade. He started playing football in the 3rd grade with the Jr. Red Devils and went on to become a Varsity Defensive End.

Donovan's parents would like to send a big THANK YOU to the teachers and staff.

"The support and encouragement we received was amazing!

Donovan your family is so proud of you and the way you continue to push yourself. We are looking forward to celebrating what the future holds for you!

Shout out to Class of 2020, it has been a wonderful experience watching you all grow! You are our future, so go out there and help make a difference!"

Reilly Bradford, who is soon to be a certified EMT, will be attending Ivy Tech (Bloomington) to pursue her degree in Paramedic Science.

Reilly has been in Pike Township schools since first grade! She played softball (9) and ran cross country (9-11). Senior year she decided to focus on her classes.

Reilly's parents shared, "We thank everyone in her village that prayed for her, uplifted and supported her through this part of her journey. You’re not finished yet baby girl. We are so proud of you and the young woman you have become. We can’t wait to see where you go and what you do. Fly baby, fly. Love Mom & Dad."

Reilly, we are so proud of and happy for you. Thank you for being a member of our #PikeFamily and allowing us to be part of your journey.

Senior Celebration

Lauren Foster has accepted an offer of direct admission into Ball State University's Bachelor of Fine Arts program where she will study Visual Communications Design.

Lauren participated in Volleyball (9-11), and served as Treasurer of the Black History Club (12). Lauren is also an alumna of the Center for Leadership Development.

Lauren's unique view of the world contributes to her artistic expression, which she hopes to use to support women and people of color in advertising.

Lauren's parents shared, "Watching Lauren grow into the young woman she is becoming has been the honor of our lives. Lauren works hard and has a caring spirit. We know she will go far, and that the best is yet to come! Chirp Chirp!"

Lauren, we are so proud of and excited for you! Thank you for allowing us to be part of your educational journey. We can't wait to watch you continue to shine.

#PikeProud #PikeFamily #ClassOf2020

Senior Celebration

D’Asia Cole will be attending Marian University in the Fall to obtain a Medical Humanities Degree. She plans on majoring in Physics and double minoring in English and Psychology in preparation for her future career as one of the few African American Obstetrician Gynecologists. D'Asia also plans to study abroad in India in her junior year of college.

D'Asia shared that she appreciates all that Pike High School continues to do for the community as well as the contribution to her education for the past 4 years. “I did it! Thank you."

D'Asia, we are so incredibly proud of all that you are and everything you aspire to become. It's been exciting to recognize your accomplishments to date and we look forward to celebrating all of your future successes. Thank you for being such an important part of our #PikeFamily.

#PikeProud #PikeFamily #ClassOf2020

post_text:
Celebrating our Seniors

Pike High School's valedictorian for the incredible class of 2020 is Heather Mansell. Heather plans to study history in preparation for a career in Federal government.

During her time at Pike, Heather's clubs and activities included marching band, wind ensemble, Indianapolis Youth Orchestra, Best Buddies, and National Honor Society. She also participated in our International Baccalaureate program and taught swimming.

Heather, whose favorite PHS memory was Prom 2019, selected Mrs. Rollings as her honored educator, sharing:

"Mrs.Rollings has been my most influential educator because she not only provided me with a stellar education, but she also displayed what it is to be successful and actively wanted her students to be successful. She was honest and encouraging, and was one of the first teachers I felt could be a
mentor and friend, as well as a teacher."

Please join us in congratulating Heather on her success & thanking her for her future service.

#PikeProud #PikeFamily #AcademicTop30 #Classof2020

post_text:
3-24-20 Update - 5:52 p.m.

Pike Family,

The Pike Red Zone Food Pantry will be open from 11 a.m. to 2 p.m. tomorrow, Wednesday, March 25th, at the Pike Freshman Center.

This Thursday will be the last official learning day prior to spring break for our traditional calendar students. If your child does not have reliable access to a device or the internet, we will communicate information about packet availability, as well as our remote learning schedule later this week.

Next week, all of our students and staff members will be on spring break. Curbside meal pick up will be available at College Park Elementary School, Guion Creek Elementary School, Eastbrook Elementary School, Deer Run Elementary School, and the Pike Freshman Center from 11 a.m. to 2 p.m. on Tuesday, March 31st and Thursday, April 2nd.

Our Pike Red Zone Food Pantry, which is located at the Pike Freshman Center, will be open from 11 a.m. to 2 p.m. on Monday (3/30), Wednesday (4/1), and Friday, (4/3).

post_text:
We have received several incredibly kind messages from people wanting to help our students and families. We are so grateful to our community for their outpouring of generosity and support.

Our Pike Red Zone Food Pantry provides food and supplies to Pike families throughout the year. They were able to provide food and necessary supplies to 27 families on Friday and will continue to do so in the coming days. The easiest way to help our Red Zone Food Pantry support our community at this time is to provide a monetary donation.

The Pike Township Educational Foundation is accepting donations via their website at https://pike-ef.org/. Please type Food Pantry in the comment section to earmark your donation.

Our counselors and social workers are available to talk and provide information regarding community resources. We encourage Pike families in need of support to call our hotline at (317) 387-2222 and leave a message.

As always, we are #PikeProud to serve our amazing community.

post_text:
Eyes on Pike - Event Canceled

Out of an abundance of caution, the decision has been made to cancel Eyes on Pike, which was scheduled to be held at Pike High School this Friday, March 13th. The large crowds the event draws and the hands-on nature of the activities presented would make following the CDC recommendations difficult. Although we very much look forward to this annual community celebration of Pike Excellence, the health, safety, and well-being, of our students, staff, and community is our top priority. We sincerely apologize for any inconvenience this may cause and appreciate your continued support.

Moving forward, decisions regarding our school and community events will be evaluated carefully and made on a case-by-case basis.

The Metropolitan School District of Pike Township 2020 - 2024 Strategic Planning Advisory Group

It is time to update our comprehensive strategic plan. The process includes a series of Strategic Planning Advisory Meetings, which include the entire Advisory Group, as well as individual Strategic Plan Committee Meetings, which will occur between our Advisory Meetings. We anticipate a total of seven meetings, with our first meeting scheduled for 6:00 p.m. Monday, March 9th, at Central Elementary School
If you are interested in participating as an Advisory Group Member, please register with the following link:

https://forms.gle/KCDtSbAchH3vRcap7

Students made clay roses for the Cancer Center, and created beautiful clay hearts for Wheeler Mission for Women and Children, our friends at the Robin Run Retirement Center, and for anyone who visits the Eagle Creek Trail across from the school. Kudos to Ms. Banks and our ECES students for using their creativity to show our community how much they care.

We wish you a happy, healthy, and safe Winter Break. Please enjoy your time off, spend quality time with family and friends, rest, recharge, and know that we look forward to welcoming everyone back on Monday, January 6, 2020.

With warm wishes, sincere appreciation & immense gratitude, we are always #PikeProud to serve you.

We are pleased to announce that our Community Education Forum will be moderated by Chalkbeat Indiana Reporter Emma Kate Fittes.

Emma Kate Fittes is a staff reporter for Chalkbeat Indiana. She covers the legislature and statewide education issues in Indiana. Before Chalkbeat, she covered suburban schools for the Indianapolis Star and Muncie Community Schools for The Star Press. Emma Kate received a bachelor’s degree in journalism from Ball State University.

Please help us ensure we ask the questions & address the issues that matter most to you by submitting your questions at https://forms.gle/vAyg91dx6TtRH2jW7.
